'''San Antonio''' ({{pron-en|<U+02CC>s<U+00E6>n<U+00E6>n<U+02C8>to<U+028A>ni.o<U+028A>}}) is the second-largest city in the [[U.S. state|state]] of [[Texas]] and the [[List of United States cities by population|seventh-largest city in the United States]] with a population of 1.4 million.<ref>http://www.census.gov/popest/cities/tables/SUB-EST2008-01.csv</ref>  The city is the [[county seat|seat]] of [[Bexar County, Texas|Bexar&nbsp;County]].  Located in the {{nowrap|[[Southwestern United States|American Southwest]]}} and the northern part of {{nowrap|[[South Texas]]}}, San Antonio is the center of [[Tejano]] culture and [[Texas]] tourism.{{Citation needed|date=January 2010}} The city is characteristic of other Southwest [[urban area|urban]] centers in which there are sparsely populated areas and a low density rate outside of the city. It was the fourth-fastest growing large city in the nation from 2000 to 2006<ref>{{cite news|url=http://money.cnn.com/2007/06/27/real_estate/fastest_growing_cities/|title=The fastest growing U.S. cities - June 28, 2007<!-- Bot generated title --> | work=CNN | date=June 28, 2007 | accessdate=May 23, 2010}}</ref> and the fifth-fastest-growing from 2007 to 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mysanantonio.com/news/local_news/SA_again_census_standout.html|title=S. A. Again Census Standout|last=Ayala|first=Elaine|date=July 1, 2009|work=San Antonio Express News|pages=B1|accessdate=2009-07-01}}</ref>  The {{nowrap|[[Greater San Antonio|San Antonio<U+2013>New Braunfels]]}} metropolitan area has a population of 2 million based on the 2008 U.S. Census estimate, making it the [[List of United States metropolitan areas|28th-largest]] metropolitan area in the U.S and third in Texas.

The city was named for the [[Portuguese people|Portuguese]] [[Anthony of Padua|St. Anthony]], whose [[calendar of saints|feast day]] is on June 13, when a Spanish expedition stopped in the area in 1691. Famous for [[San Antonio Missions National Historic Park|Spanish missions]], the [[Alamo Mission in San Antonio|Alamo]], the [[San Antonio River Walk|River Walk]], the [[Tower of the Americas]], the [[Alamo Bowl]], and host to [[SeaWorld San Antonio|Seaworld]] and [[Six Flags Fiesta Texas]] theme parks, the city is visited by approximately 26 million tourists per year according to the San Antonio Convention and Visitors Bureau.  The city is home to the four-time NBA champion [[San Antonio Spurs]] and the annual [[San Antonio Stock Show & Rodeo]], one of the largest in the country.

San Antonio has a strong military presence<U+2014>it is home to [[Fort Sam Houston]], [[Lackland Air Force Base]], [[Randolph Air Force Base]], and [[Brooks City-Base]], with [[Camp Bullis]] and Camp Stanley outside the city. [[Kelly Air Force Base]] operated out of San Antonio until 2001, when the airfield was transferred over to Lackland AFB and the remaining portions of the base became [[Port San Antonio]], an industrial/business park. San Antonio is home to five Fortune 500 companies and to the [[South Texas Medical Center]], the only medical research and care provider in the South Texas region.
