San Antonio is located near 29.5<U+00B0>N 98.5<U+00B0>W. According to the [[United States Census Bureau]], in 2000 the city had a total area of {{convert|412.07|mi2|km2|sigfig=5}} <U+2014> {{convert|407.56|mi2|km2|sigfig=5}} (98.9%) of land and {{convert|4.51|mi2|km2|sigfig=3}}
(1.1%) of water. The city sits on the [[Balcones Escarpment]].The altitude of San Antonio is {{convert|772|ft|m|0}} above sea level.

The primary source of drinking water for the city is the [[Edwards Aquifer]]. Impounded in 1962 and 1969, respectively, [[Victor Braunig Lake]] and [[Calaveras Lake (Texas)|Calaveras Lake]] were among the first [[reservoir (water)|reservoirs]] in the country built to use recycled treated wastewater for [[power plant]] cooling, reducing the amount of groundwater needed for [[electricity|electrical]] generation.

